<DOC><DOCNO> AP881004-0152 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-88 2005EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-BRF--ConservationPayments     10-04 0152</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Conservation Payments,150</SECOND><HEAD>Farmers to Get $1.2 Billion from Conservation Program</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About $1.2 billion in cash payments soon willbe made to farmers under the Conservation Reserve Program, theAgriculture Department said Tuesday.   Milton Hertz, executive vice president of the department'sCommodity Credit Corp., said the payments are rental fees for landcontracts signed in the 1986, 1987 and 1988 fiscal years.   Under the program, farmers agree to take highly erodiblecropland from production for 10 years. In return, USDA helps payfor planting the land to protective grass or trees and providesannual rental payments over the 10-year contract period.   The goal under the program is to take 40 million to 45 millionacres of highly erodible land from crop production by 1990. Morethan 25.5 million acres have have been officially enrolled, and anadditional 3.4 million acres were offered by farmers in a recentsignup.</TEXT></DOC>